<TD>
<IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/icons/icon1.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="ABSCENTER">
<FONT SIZE="1" color="#000000" face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
posted December 19, 2001 06:12 PM &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_profile&u=00001486" target=_blank>
<IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/profile_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Profile for Foddzer"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://" target=_new><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/homepage.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Author's Homepage"></A> &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=private_message&u=00001486"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/priv_message.gif" BORDER='0' ALT="Send New Private Message"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=edit_post&f=21&t=000279&reply_num=000000&u=00001486"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/edit_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Edit/Delete Post"></A> &nbsp;&nbsp;<A HREF="http://forums.castersrealm.com/cgi-bin/daoc/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=reply&f=21&t=000279&replyto=000000"><IMG SRC="http://forums.castersrealm.com/daoc/quote_ubb6.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Reply With Quote"></A>
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#12350C">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Hi everybody. I am trying to write a guide to sorcery for my guild, would appreciate comments, corrections, and additions. Thanks to !3ullseye for his excellent guide that helped me started in sorcerey, I tried not to plagiarize, honest!<P><BR>The Sorcerer<P><BR>Pros: <P>Awesome debuff and crowd control abilities. Minor movement speed buff.  Fun pets. Subtle and mysterious powers &lt;:-D...<P><BR>Cons:<P>It is often time consuming to find a pet. Pet goes *poof* when zoning, logging off, or (worst of all) when you go linkdead. Pets move and heal slowly. Sorcerers die often when in full groups due to issues with AE spells/mezz. Sorcerers can easily cause party wipeouts. Class sometimes misunderstood/mistrusted by others, hard to find groups compared to most other classes.<P><BR>Spell specialization:<P>Sorcerers have 3 different spell lines (mind, body, and matter), each of those 3 spell lines are divided into a base and a specialist line of spells. Sorcerers automatically get all of the spells in each of the base lines equivalent to thier level. Spells from the 3 specialzation lines are obtained when specialization points are put into the respective specializations. Spell effectiveness increases as more points are put into its respective spell line. I want high specialization levels particularly to keep resisted spells to a minimum (this may be totally level based but I think spec level figures into resists). <P>A sorcerer can choose to put points into either all 3 lines, just 2 of the lines, or fully specialize in just one line. It is not recommended to fully specialize in one line as the advantages are minimal and the disadvantages are great. Putting  points into all 3 lines will result in a more versatile character that has generally lower spell effectiveness than a character with all points in just 2 lines.<P> So far, my character has most points into mind (1/2 to 3/4 of level) with the rest into body (it is tempting to put a few into matter though). <P><BR>Base spell lines:<P>Mind base:<P>1) confusion<BR>2) single target mezmerization  <BR>3) forgetfulnes  <BR>4) movement speed buff <P>Body base:<P>1) drain    <BR>2)  single target strength debuff                   <BR>3)  single target root <P>Matter base: <P>1) damage over time (slow timer)	        <BR>2) self armor factor buff<P><BR>Specialization spell lines:<P>Mind specialization (domination):<P>1) charm  <BR>2) strength/constitution area effect debuff   <BR>3) area effect mezmerization<P>Body specialization (disorientation):<P>1) direct damage<BR>2) dexterity/quickness area effect debuff<BR>3) area effect root  <P>Matter specialization (telekinesis): <P>1) damage over time (quick timer)<BR>2) dexterity debuff <P><BR>Pets:<P>Sorcerers can charm so called "human-like" creatures, not all humanoids can be charmed. Creatures like giants, humanoid elementals, and some named NPCs cannot be charmed. Sorcerers can only charm creatures of a level equal to and lower than thier own (given they have a high enough mind specialization). Pets generally remain charmed indefinitely until you either die, cross a zone boundary, or go linkdead. If pet gets very wounded and will take a long time to heal it is sometimes best to release it and charm a new one.<P><BR>Spells:<P>The confuse line of spells is hazardous to use but can be extremely effective. When cast on an opponent, confuse will cause the opponent to select a random target from among your group members every few seconds. This causes the opponent to run about like a chicken with it's head cut off. At higher levels, this spell line will cause the opponent to randomly target other baddies a certain percentage of the time. Confuse should be used with great caution when battling opponents that can kill any of your party members in a hit or 2. It is easy to underestimate just how effective confuse is in reducing damage output from opponents, they can waste huge amounts of time running from target to target, often never even attacking. It is important for melee'ers to use the /stick command when confuse is cast. Confuse if often good to cast if one of your party's melee'ers is taking too much damage. <P>The amnesia line of spells is good to use when you absolutely need to save a party member (usually a healer). When cast on an opponent they will continue attacking their current target, but its agression level will be set to the minimum, damage from anybody else in your party will pull the opponent off. <P>Never underestimate the power of debuffs (spells that reduce opponent's strength, constitution, dexterity, and quickness).   The debuff spells cost very little power to cast and cause a low amount of agression. It is best to apply debuffs when opponents are still near full health near the beginning of battles. The single target strength and dexterity debuffs are often the best spells to "pull" single opponents out of crowded areas. Be careful of agressing unintended targets when using the area effect debuff spells. A single opponent can be hit with the area effect str/con debuff, area effect qui/dex debuff, single target str debuff, and single target dex debuff all stacked for a debilitating effect!<P>Mass mesmerization is used far more often than the single target mesmerization spell. Mass mezz costs about the same as single target and lasts virtually as long (depending on mind spec level). Opponents that have either built up too much agression or have taken more than 10% damage ( not absolutely sure about the agression part) cannot be mesmerized. Use the cripple (root) spell line to get away from opponents that cannot be mezzed. Each time an opponent is re-charmed, the mezz will wear off in half the amount of time as the previous one. <P>The body specialization direct damage spells are more power efficient but take longer to cast than the body base drain spell. I almost always prefer drain, only using the direct damage spells in select situations. <P>The damage over time spells are power efficient and are useful when fighting tougher mobs. Cast DoTs near the beginning of battles but be careful of causing unwanted agression. <P><BR>Solo strategy:<P>In order to minimize down time, try to balance the amount of time it takes your pet to heal with the amount of time for you to regain power. It is often better to go below half power nuking away than to let your pet take damage.<P>Here is an example of one method to attack a powerful single creature where there are no other creatures in the immediate area:  first cast area effect quickness/dexterity debuff spell, then tell your pet to attack so that it gets the opponent's attention, then area effect strength/constitution debuff, then single target strength debuff, then damage over time, then nuke away with drain spells. Your pet should have sufficient agression directed against it by the time you are done debuffing that your damaging spells will not cause your opponent to go after you.  The wide variety of spell effects directed against one target makes for a spectacular display. Even the occasional red++ con creature can be soloed with this and similar methods. Soloing reds is not generally a good idea but can be fun!! <P>Baddies that are naturally grouped together can be taken all at once to maximize experience and profit. One method is to cast area effect strength/constitution debuff on the group at maximum range, then cast area effect dexterity/quickness debuff, then cast area effect mesmerize (mezz can be casted first too, probably a better plan), they should all be frozen a few paces from you at this point. Have pet attack one of the baddies and sprint about 20 paces away, then cast single target strength debuff and drain till it is dead, have pet attack next baddie and continue till they are all dead. Whopping amounts of exp and loot can be had when taking large groups but it is easy to have a mishap and die if you are not very careful. <P><BR>Group strategy:<P>Pets can be very nice to have in groups but are usually not required. Many sorcerers make the error of wasting time fiddling with pets when they should be concentrating on helping the party with debuffs and crowd control. <P>Debuff every baddie your group battles, you are the debuff master of Albion. <P>If there is a bad pull and you know your party will get overwhelmed, attempt to mesmerize any baddies before they reach your party, it can help to announce your mezzes if possible. Try to educate the party in what the mesmerization spell effect looks like and what its effect is (opponents cannot move or do anythiing until they are hit or mezz wears off). It is often a good idea for melee'ers to be using the /assist command on the group puller when mesmerization is involved. <P>Attempt to save the healer(s) at all costs, amnesia or confusion will usually do the trick. Sorcerers should attempt to save any other party member that is in trouble, confusion or amnesia will usually do the trick. <P><BR>Staves: <P>Use a "sorcerer focus" staff at all times. If a sorcerer specific staff is not used, all spells are cast at 125% power usage. There are also staves that allow 10% power savings with spells  in specific spell-lines that are at or below the specified level (IMO this savings is usually inconsequential, items that give boosts to spec lines are much more desireable).<P>RvR:<P>I have done little RvR and really have no clue about this. My hope is to assist in battles with mass mesmerization to freeze groups of opponents and debuffs so severe they become crippling. Perhaps overconfident single opponents could be lured into strategically placed pet-traps and finished with a crippling debuff sequence? Muahah. &lt;:o)<P>Foddzer
</FONT>
