<HR size="1" color="#12350C">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
Why compare ourselves to everyone else?  You know, a Cleric heals a heck of a lot better than a Friar.  An Armsman fights better than a Mercenary.  <P>I would think every class offers something unique that can be useful, if done correctly.  The problem is, I don't think we Sorcerers do anything particularly well.  But that's okay!  We're versatile.  We can Mez, Nuke, Debuff, Increase Run Speed, Root, DoT, Confuse, Memory Wipe...if we're in a group, maybe we can be the Mezzer.  Oh, what's that, a Minstrel joined?  Fine, let them Mez since they have little better to do, and I'll instead Nuke and Memory Wipe if someone is near dying and healing power is low.  Oh, we have ourselves a Wizard?  Okay, maybe debuff the snot out of them then (yes, debuffing does make some differences, fighters have told me that indeed they can hit more often, which is pretty useful against reds and purples).  And if viable group members are scarce, we can just about do it all.  We can mez the adds, then turn to the main, hit out a Debuff, then nuke the sucker to death, then reapply the mez to one while repeating your process with the second, etc. etc.<P>Someone said that we need to sell ourselves more, and I agree with that wholly.  Sure, we don't do anything better than anyone else.  Maybe that really wasn't our intent.  Maybe versatility is what we do really well.  But a group of 8 with a Sorcerer is at least better than a group of 7 without one, and if you keep a level head and know what to do and when (we aren't allowed to just sit back and cast the same spell over and over, it doesn't always work that way with us), then you can be successful.<P>I'm sure it's different with everyone, but I really haven't seen much of the horrible troubles that everyone says makes us worthless.  We have our uses, just need to know when and where and how.<P>~Sigma<BR>26 Sorcerer<BR>Percival
</FONT>
